04188nam a22006255i 9780822375746DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20152015ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014025037  a97808223757467 a10.1515/97808223757462doi  a(DE-B1597)553953  a(OCoLC)899276048  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aRC889b.Z48 2015 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aZhang, Everett Yuehong, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Impotence Epidemic :bMen's Medicine and Sexual Desire in Contemporary China /cEverett Yuehong Zhang. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b18 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Global Health: Evidence, Efficacy, Ethnography00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Impotence Epidemic in China -- tPART I: SOCIETY AND STATE -- tCHAPTER 1. The Birth of Nanke (Men's Medicine) -- tCHAPTER 2. Sexual Repression -- tCHAPTER 3. One Thousand Bodies of Impotence -- tCHAPTER 4. Impotence, Family, and Women -- tPART II: POTENCY AND LIFE -- tCHAPTER 5. The Loss of Jing (Seminal Essence) and the Revival of Yangsheng (the Cultivation of Life) -- tCHAPTER 6. Bushen (Nourishing the Kidney), Shugan (Smoothing out the Liver), or Taking the Great Brother (Viagra) -- tCHAPTER 7. Potency Is Fullness of Life -- tCONCLUSION: "If Shen (the Kidney) Is Strong, Life Is Good" -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the 1990s China has seen a dramatic increase in the number of men seeking treatment for impotence. Everett Yuehong Zhang argues in The Impotence Epidemic that this trend represents changing public attitudes about sexuality in an increasingly globalized China. In this ethnography he shifts discussions of impotence as a purely neurovascular phenomenon to a social one. Zhang contextualizes impotence within the social changes brought by recent economic reform and through the production of various desires in post-Maoist China. Based on interviews with 350 men and their partners from Beijing and Chengdu, and concerned with de-mystifying and de-stigmatizing impotence, Zhang suggests that the impotence epidemic represents not just trauma and suffering, but also a contagion of individualized desire and an affirmation for living a full life. For Zhang, studying male impotence in China is one way to comprehend the unique experience of Chinese modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aImpotencexTreatmentxChina. 0aImpotencexTreatmentzChina. 0aImpotencexTreatment. 0aMedicine, Chinese. 0aMenxSexual behaviorxChina. 0aMenxSexual behaviorzChina. 0aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Security. 0aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Services & Welfare. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822375746zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822375746423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822375746.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles